as "the horrible traffik in humans". Petitions to Parliament came from remote islands in Shetland as well as from large public meetings in cities. In a land steeped in religion, ministers and church leaders took the lead in giving theological support to the cause of abolition. The contributions of five London Scots who were pivotal to the campaign throughout Britain are set against opposition to abolition from many Scots with commercial interests in the slave trade and the sugar plantations.Missionaries and miners, trades guilds and lawyers all played their parts in challenging slavery. Many of their struggles and frustrations are detailed for the first time in an assessment of the unique contribution made by Scotland and the Scots to the destruction of an institution whose effects are still with us today."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAntislavery movementsxHistoryx18th centuryxScotland. 0aAntislavery movementsxHistoryx19th centuryxScotland. 0aAntislavery movementszScotlandxHistoryy18th century. 0aAntislavery movementszScotlandxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryx18th centuryxScotland. 0aPublic opinionxHistoryx19th centuryxScotland. 0aPublic opinionzScotlandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPublic opinionzScotlandxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavery and the churchxHistoryx18th centuryxScotland. 0aSlavery and the churchxHistoryx19th centuryxScotland. 0aSlavery and the churchzScotlandxHistoryy18th century. 0aSlavery and the churchzScotlandxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryxPublic opinionxHistoryx18th centuryxScotland. 0aSlaveryxPublic opinionxHistoryx19th centuryxScotlandxScotlandxSchottland. 0aSlaveryzScotlandxPublic opinionxHistoryy18th century. 0aSlaveryzScotlandxPublic opinionxHistoryy19th century. 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Eu